  "prompt": "What are the end of service benefits of an ex-president of the USA? How much is the ex-president\u2019s pension? How much is he paid in allowances?",
  "response": "The end of service benefits for an ex-president of the United States are outlined in the Former Presidents Act. These benefits include:\n\n1. **Pension**: Former presidents receive a pension that is equivalent to the salary of a Cabinet Secretary, which is pegged to the Executive Level I pay schedule. As of 2023, this amount is around $223,500 per year.\n\n2. **Allowances**: Former presidents are entitled to certain allowances, including:\n   - **Office Space**: They receive funding for office space and staff, which varies based on the location and size of the office.\n   - **Staff**: Funding is available for hiring office staff.\n   - **Travel Expenses**: Former presidents are reimbursed for travel expenses related to their continued activities as former presidents.\n   - **Medical Care**: If a former president was in office prior to 1997, they are eligible for treatment in military hospitals. For those who served after 1997, they can purchase health insurance through the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program.\n\n3. **Secret Service Protection**: All former presidents and their immediate family members are entitled to lifetime Secret Service protection.\n\nThese benefits are in place to ensure that former presidents can maintain their dignity and security while transitioning out of public office. The pension and allowances let former presidents engage in post-presidential activities, such as philanthropic work, writing, and speaking engagements.",
